text: often times it's the women senators
Democrats and Republicans who can cross
party lines who can find that common
ground build consensus and then move
legislation forward I was drawn into
politics when I was a little girl so
there was no real aha moment here it
happened a long time ago and it was
really with my grandmother who loved
politics and she was a woman well ahead
of her time who 75 years ago recognized
that women didn't have much of a voice
in government or politics and so I
learned really at her knee how important
women's voices are how important
grassroots activism is how important
what you do with your time is and so I
had a great love and admiration for
public service and and grassroots
activism we only have 20 women in the
Senate we need 50 or 51 we only have 18%
in the House of Representatives again it
should represent the nation we should
have women representing the full
population of the United States and I
think when women's voices are heard
outcomes will be better oftentimes I see
an issue as a mom so even sexual assault
in the military I imagine what if this
happened to one of my two sons I just
spent the last 45 minutes talking to two
survivors men who were raped in the
military something has to be done on
their behalf that makes me not only
passionate but determined to make sure
they can be heard and so it's all about
making sure everyday people have a voice
here in Washington what I feel my job is
not only to listen but then to find the
solution and reach out across the aisle
work on common ground and build support
from there what I found to be
interesting with among my women female
colleagues is that they actually are
quite good at building consensus and
finding the areas that we agree and we
actually spend time with each other we
try to get to know each other outside of
work we have quarterly dinners so we can
get it to know each other as people as
daughters as wives as mothers and it
helps because I want my colleagues to be
successful whether they're Democrats or
Republicans I want to be able to
legislate with them and find things that
we have in common and actually solve
problems and that seems to be a shared
characteristic amongst the women the
Senate
